-- South African Stocks Extend Losses, Led by Anglo American, BHP and Simmers
-- Janice Kew
-- 2010-07-05T15:48:34Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-05/south-african-stocks-extend-losses-led-by-anglo-american-bhp-and-simmers.html

          
          
             South Africa’s  FTSE/JSE Africa All
Share Index  lost 131.89, or 0.5 percent, to 26,182.67 in
Johannesburg, extending last week’s 3.5 percent drop.  
 The following are among the most active stocks in the South
African market today.  
 BHP Billiton Ltd.  (BIL SJ), the world’s largest mining
company, dropped 5.15 rand, or 2.6 percent, to 196.55 rand,
bringing its slide this year to 17 percent, as investors
speculated the strength of the economic recovery decreased.
 Anglo American Plc  (AGL SJ) declined 6.51 rand, or 2.4 percent,
to 263.99 rand.  
 “There are some concerns that Chinese growth may slow and
that affects the large mining companies,”  Ferdi Heyneke , an
equity trader at Afrifocus Securities Ltd., said by phone from
Johannesburg.  
 Cie Financiere Richemont SA  (CFR SJ), the world’s second-
largest luxury-goods maker, increased for a second day, climbing
29 cents, or 1.1 percent, to 26.91 rand after BofA Merrill Lynch
Global Research analysts called the jewelry maker a “compelling
buy opportunity,” raising its recommendation to “buy” from
“neutral.”  
      Jasco Electronics Holdings Ltd.  (JSC SJ) fell 3 cents, or
2.3 percent, to 1.27 rand, its biggest fall in more than a week.
The telecommunications company said it was in talks which may
affect its shares.  
 Simmer & Jack Mines Ltd.  (SIM SJ) slid for a third straight
day, dropping 2 cents, or 2.1 percent, to 92 rand. Gold for
immediate delivery fell as much as $5.55, or 0.5 percent, to
$1,206.05 an ounce in London.  AngloGold Ashanti Ltd.  (ANG SJ)
shed 4.75 rand, or 1.5 percent, to 314.25 rand.  
